Conestoga Capital Advisors, LLC Raises Its Holdings in Medidata Solutions, Inc. (MDSO) Stock Last Quarter 












































 Finance DailyDaily markets, commodities, personal finance and economic newsConestoga Capital Advisors, LLC Raises Its Holdings in Medidata Solutions, Inc. (MDSO) Stock Last Quarter
July 21, 2017 By Ted Blackburn Tweet
        Advertisement



Medidata Solutions, Inc. (NASDAQ:MDSO). 
 Conestoga Capital Advisors, LLC bought 36,910 shares during the last quarter increasing its exposure to Medidata Solutions, Inc.  by 6.0%.  Its position was worth $50,904,000 an increase of $15,481,000 as of the end of the quarter. 
 Here are some other firms who have updated their holdings.   As of quarter end Bb&t Corp had sold 40 shares trimming its position 0.7%. The value of the investment in (MDSO) went from $333,000 to $448,000 a change of $115,000 for the reporting period. As of the end of the quarter Peregrine Capital Management LLC had disposed of  a total of 69,085 shares trimming its stake by 19.2%. The value of the investment in MDSO increased from $20,587,000 to $22,793,000 increasing 10.7% quarter to quarter.
 As of the end of the quarter Malaga Cove Capital, LLC had sold 198 shares trimming its holdings by 0.5%. The value of the company’s investment in Medidata Solutions, Inc. went from $2,194,000 to $2,976,000 a change of 35.6% since the last quarter.
  July 20 investment analysts at Morgan Stanley left the company rating at “Overweight” but raised the price expectation  to $86.00 from $56.00. On June 6, 2017 Bank of America starting coverage on MDSO setting a rating of “Buy”.        Advertisement






 On November 22 Jefferies kept the stock rating at “Underperform” and lowered the price target from $55.00 to $46.00. September 13 investment analysts at Deutsche Bank held the company rating at “Buy” and raised the price expectation from $41.00 to $58.00.
 On July 21, 2016 the stock rating was rated “Market Perform” in a report from Wells Fargo down from the previous “Outperform” rating. On April 26 analysts at Leerink Swann issued its first research report on the stock with a rating of “Underperform”.
 The company is unchanged from yesterday’s close of $75.78.  It is trading at $75.78 which is just under the 50 day moving average of $77.53 and which is a tad above the 200 day moving average of $63.59.  The 50 day moving average went down by -2.26% and the 200 day average went up $12.19 or +19.18%. 
 The P/E ratio is currently 128.66 and the market cap of the company is 4.27B.  In the last earnings report the EPS was $0.59 and is expected to be $1.28 for the current year with 56,312,000 shares now outstanding.  Analysts expect next quarter’s EPS will be $0.35 and the next full year EPS is projected to be $1.51. 
 Investors are feeling more bearish of late if you consider the rise in short interest.  The stock realized a rise in short interest between June 15, 2017 and May 31, 2017 of 3.82%.  Short interest increased from 4,080,061 to 4,235,987 over that period.  Days to cover decreased from 9.7 to 6.8 and the percentage of shorted shares was 0.08% on May 31.
